AGI - There is a time when pain also turns into something magical. A moment in which daily suffering, the battles of small creatures fighting for life, find a voice, a melody, a symphony that tells not only fear but also confidence in tomorrow. And it is precisely in this delicate plot that the extraordinary union between two seemingly distant worlds is realized: that of neonathology and that of music.> Doctors are daily faced with the challenge of treating premature infants or serious diseases: a silent battle, made of small hearts that strive to beat, of monitors that emit incessant sounds, signals that may seem threatening but that are, at the same time, the breath of life itself.
In particular, thanks to Dr. Raffaella Cavallone, a neonatologue of Newborn Intensive Therapy at the “Di Venere” hospital in Bari, those “beeps” that accompany the daily life in intensive therapy, alarms that constantly measure the boundary between life and death, have become music among the hands of the pianist and master Emanuele Arciuli. >E could not be different with the love encounter of two souls: “Our private correspondence, as comrades – tells Agi Dr. Cavallone with a veil of emotion – has become an inspiration for Emanuele, who has decided to harmonize those who for me are alarms and daily sounds of my work, to join him to his. As if it was another twist of suffering, to tell that behind those who suffer there is always a great light ready to rise."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The sweetness of the black and white piano keys, touched by the expert hands of Arciuli, has given new life to the cold and aseptic sounds of hospital surveillance instruments.> Its musical composition has transformed the noise into harmony, the urgency in beauty. A gesture that goes beyond medical therapy and that also embraces the soul, offering serenity, comfort and a radius of optimism. In this period, the appointment of Chief Michele Quercia brought new lifeblood to the department. His sensitivity to this extraordinary artistic initiative gave way to a deeper reflection on how art can become a therapeutic tool, able to alleviate tensions and fears that pervade the department.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
As the primary tells, art has the power to transform pain into something positive: “In an environment such as neonatal intensive therapy, where tension and fear are constant, where the sound of monitors makes the daily work of doctors and nurses – explains to Agi – there is a possibility to transform it into a resource: music”.> The same alarms, which in everyday life evoke an alteration of vital parameters, have become sounds that not only infuse serenity, but represent life evocation.
Music, in fact, is a universal language that speaks directly to the soul. It can overcome the barrier of words, it expresses deep emotions, creating a connection involving doctors, nurses, patients and family members. It is not only a relief for small patients, but also for their parents, who find in the melody a channel of expression and comfort, a way to face anxiety and fear that accompany them at such a difficult time.
“Scientific studies have shown that music therapy in vulnerable infants can regulate heart rate, improve respiratory rhythm and even promote weight gain,” the doctor explains. "In the symphony that arises between the monitor and the piano, each beat becomes part of a larger project: that of a life that struggles to assert itself." Master Arciuli, with his art, gave voice to those "beeps" of the devices, > making them part of a composition that tells not only the strength of existence, but also the beauty of rebirth.
The incidence of premature infants (born before 37 weeks of gestation) in Italy ranges between 7 and 10%, meaning about 25 thousand -30 thousand born a year. In the last decade, the combined obstetric-neonatological management has greatly changed the incidence of the preterminal parts and survival, especially of the lowest gestational age, but above all has improved the outcome of the preterminal infants, that is the remote outcome of neuromotor, cognitive and behavioral disabilities.
"To enter a neonatal intensive care department means to confront each day with the subtle border between fragility and trust in the future – concludes Quercia. Premature infants or severe pathologies are incredibly small beings, but with an extraordinary force.> For me, being here means having the privilege of accompanying them, together with their families, on a path that, thanks to the science and dedication of all staff, can lead to great victories." And so, in this corner of hope and struggle for life, music and medicine intertwine, creating a symphony that, like a heartbeat, reminds us that, even in the darkest moment, a vital spark can always resonate with sweetness and love.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

